    "short_descriptor": "17th-century New England origin, 1930s-1950s American revival.",
    "background_prose": "Cape Cod architecture originated in 17th-century New England, where settlers built compact 1.5-story homes with steep roofs to shed snow and central chimneys for heat. The Cape Cod Revival of the 1930s through the 1950s, especially through the work of Royal Barry Wills, brought the style to suburban America. Key features include the 1.5-story height, a steep gabled roof, central chimney, two front-facing dormer windows, weathered cedar-shingle siding, and a compact symmetric front. Florida's coastal-cottage builds borrow the style heavily.",
